  "text": "The Android View rendering pipeline is orchestrated through a coordinated sequence of operations:\n\n1. **ViewRootImpl** (core/java/android/view/ViewRootImpl.java): The root connection between the window manager and the view hierarchy. The `scheduleTraversals()` method (line 2948) initiates rendering by posting a callback to the Choreographer for VSYNC synchronization. It also contains `doTraversal()` (line 2968) which triggers `performTraversals()` (line 3422), the main method that executes the complete measurement, layout, and drawing passes.\n\n2. **Choreographer** (core/java/android/view/Choreographer.java): The VSYNC-driven frame scheduler that synchronizes rendering with the display refresh rate. The `postFrameCallback()` method (line 613) allows registration of frame callbacks, while `scheduleVsyncLocked()` (line 1059) requests synchronization with the next VSYNC signal. Choreographer acts as the timing hub that prevents jank by aligning all rendering work with display refresh cycles.\n\n3. **View** (core/java/android/view/View.java): The fundamental building block containing the three-phase rendering pipeline: `measure()` (line 28137) performs a top-down pass to determine view dimensions, `layout()` (line 25385) positions children relative to the parent, and `draw()` (line 24849) paints the view hierarchy to a canvas.\n\n4. **ThreadedRenderer** (core/java/android/view/ThreadedRenderer.java): The hardware-accelerated rendering implementation (line 63) that extends HardwareRenderer. It manages rendering on a dedicated render thread, converting view drawing operations into GPU commands. The `draw()` method (line 885) handles the actual hardware-accelerated rendering pipeline.\n\n5. **HardwareRenderer** (graphics/java/android/graphics/HardwareRenderer.java): The base class (line 82) providing the framework for GPU-accelerated rendering. It manages the render thread, GPU context, and surface management, serving as the bridge between the view system and